descript.supplinf: This data set was created as a foundational element for the Taylor County Land Information System. The building feature class provides a digital representation of all address building locations within Taylor County and is to be used in conjunction with developed digital road centerline, site access, and driveway feature classes. The building feature class was intended to be used to enhance addressing information within the County.
descript.purpose:
This layer is intended for reference and mapping purposes, and may be used for basic applications such as viewing, querying, and map output production, or to provide a basemap to support graphical overlays and analysis with other spatial data.
[This data set was created as a foundational element for Taylor County. The building feature class provides a digital representation of all primary buildings or structures within Vernon County and is to be used in conjunction with developed digital road centerline, site access points, and driveway feature classes. The building feature class is intended to be used to enhance addressing information within the County. It is a subset to the site access points.]
descript.abstract: This point data layer represents addresses for Taylor Couny, Wisconsin at year-end 2016. It is a feature class within the geodatabase 'Taylor_Addresses_YE2016.gdb'. [Buildings represent a collection of points spatially located over the main building for any given address. For the most part, in urban areas, there is not a building point located unless the main building would not be physically visible from the road. The data was developed to only show the main structure for a given address, meaning that there is only one building point per address . In the case of duplexes or multi family structures additional building points and site access points are added. By only having one building point per address and one site access point, a one to one relationship is maintained with the site access point.]

procstep.procdesc: Step 1: Convert delivered address points shapefile to feature class. Cleaned out unneeded information and added additional necessary fields determined by the counties needs. At this point, domains were also created based on county standards.
Step 2: Placed address point over building from imagery or created building point and placed over building on imagery.

Step 3: Attributed the building point with address or confirmed existing address from address points delivered. Also attributed unique information such as the parcel identification number with a attribute transfer. Unique address id was created in an automated process as points were created.

Step 4: Missing addresses were searched for in the property tax database and ANI/ALI. Additional addresses were then created as described in steps 1-3. At this point, modifiers were also attributed in the addresses.
Step 5: The building point was copied to the site access layer.

Step 6: All spatial attributes were assigned to the building points. This included information such as zip codes, ESN and MCD. All buildings along boundary lines were examined to ensure the correct number was assigned.

Step 7: Table was QC'ed for missing and incorrect data. This includes table analysis within itself and joined to the roads and site access tables. This ensures that the repetitive data remains consistent.

attrdomv.udom: Name of the person who last edited the record. Entry at the time of delivery is ADC. As county updates the data, the name will change.
Core part of the road name without prefix direction or street type suffix.
Address number from hardcopy map. If address conflicts with sources it is noted. Other sources used for comparison are ANI/ALI and property tax database.
Unique number assigned from the hardcopy address map and/or ANI/ALI. No modifier assigned in the city/village limits. When no address number was found, the entry is left blank.

attr.attrdef: Full address composed of the alpha numeric address and the road name.

attrdomv.udom: When no road name or alpha numeric address number exist the entry is left blank.

attr.attrdef: Unique numeric value assigned for each address

attrdomv.udom: Assigned starting at 1. Numbers not necessarily consecutive due to addresses being added and deleted.

Number assigned based on the parcel address in the property tax database. Not assigned entry means there is a discrepancy with the alignment or information in the tax database. When discrepancies exist, a comment is made.

attr.attrdef: Source from which the address originates.
Official name assigned-same name as in the roads.

attrdomv.udom: Designated name based on available sources. Problems with names are identified in the comment field. Entry of no name means no name was found from available sources.

attr.attrdef: Designates if the location of the building point is believed accurate.
Additional information regarding problems or issues, typically not a common occurence.

attrdomv.udom: Range of comments describing problems or issues that cannot be generalized.

attr.attrdef: Unique numeric value assigned to the road arc its addressed from.

attrdomv.udom: Unique numeric values assigned to each road arc starting at 1000. Values are not consecutive due to roads being added and deleted from the database. This is a direct link between the road and the address.

attr.attrdef: Zip code the address is in.

overview.eaover: Attribute information remains the same as given by the author of the data. [Many fields in this dataset work together. For example, road_name is the complete name and pd, street and st make up the road_name. If any one of these changes then the other 3 may need to be checked and changed. This example also shows that the dynamic data that will need continual updating. Other fields are more static and will not require changes. Because buildings are a subset of the site access points, changes made to one dataset will have to be made to the related dataset also.]
